                    ('When a novel uses a protagonist\'s struggle against social norms to critique those norms, the novel is:', ['Using character as a vehicle for social critique — the individual story becomes a lens on the larger social structure', 'Simply telling a story about an unusual or exceptional individual without broader significance', 'Providing a historical record of the norms of its period', 'Making a moral argument that the protagonist is wrong to resist']),
                    ('The protagonist of a novel embodies social critique most effectively when:', ['Their situation is representative of a broader pattern — not just an individual exception — and the text frames their struggle in social terms', 'They explicitly state the social critique in dialogue or interior monologue', 'They are entirely virtuous and the social structure is entirely evil', 'They succeed in overcoming social constraint by the end of the work']),
