                [
                    _t('Aristotelian Dramatic Structure', 'Aristotle\'s Poetics identifies six elements of tragedy: plot, character, thought, diction, spectacle, and melody. Key structural elements: exposition, rising action, climax, falling action, denouement (resolution).', 'Aristotle\'s tragic hero has a hamartia (fatal flaw) that leads to their downfall; catharsis is the emotional purging of pity and fear the audience experiences.', 'AP®: apply Aristotelian concepts to analyze a dramatic work\'s structure and its effects on the audience.'),
                    _t('Stage Directions and Theatrical Elements', 'Plays exist as both texts and performances; stage directions, set design, and theatrical conventions are part of the literary analysis.', 'Stage directions can be as rich with meaning as dialogue — Beckett\'s stage directions in "Waiting for Godot" are essential to the work\'s meaning.', 'AP®: analyze how a playwright\'s stage directions contribute to the play\'s meaning.'),
                    _t('Dialogue and Subtext', 'Dramatic dialogue is more compressed and multi-layered than prose narration; what characters don\'t say (subtext) is often as important as what they do say.', 'Subtext in drama: characters rarely say exactly what they mean — their indirect language, evasions, and silences communicate as much as their words.', 'AP®: analyze how a play\'s dialogue reveals character psychology and theme through what is said and what is left unsaid.'),
                ],
