                    ('A postcolonial reading of a literary text examines:', ['How colonialism shapes narrative perspective, power relations, and representation in the text', 'The geographic settings in which colonial events take place', 'Whether the author was from a formerly colonized country', 'Only texts written during the period of active colonial rule']),
                    ('When analyzing how class shapes characters\' choices in a Victorian novel, students should explain:', ['How the specific class structure of Victorian England determines what options are available to different characters and what is at stake in their choices', 'What class the author belonged to and how that affected their writing', 'Whether class distinctions in the novel are accurate to actual Victorian class structure', 'Only whether the protagonist is upper or lower class']),
                    ('Reading a canonical Western text "through the eyes of" a marginalized character most directly:', ['Reveals power structures and assumptions that are naturalized in the dominant perspective and invisible without this shift', 'Produces a less accurate reading because it departs from authorial intent', 'Is only appropriate for works explicitly about race, gender, or class', 'Requires using only historical scholarship rather than the literary text itself']),
